{"id": "rag_1", "question": "How do I handle GPU out of memory errors?", "ideal_answer": "Use smaller batch sizes, enable gradient accumulation, use mixed precision (fp16), or reduce model size. MONAI supports these via transforms and trainer settings.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["GPU memory management", "batch size tuning", "gradient accumulation"]}
{"id": "rag_2", "question": "What's the difference between Normalize and NormalizeIntensity?", "ideal_answer": "Normalize rescales to [0, 1] or [-1, 1] range. NormalizeIntensity uses mean/std normalization (z-score). Choose based on whether you want range-based or statistical normalization.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["normalization methods", "intensity scaling", "preprocessing"]}
{"id": "rag_3", "question": "How do I apply data augmentation in MONAI?", "ideal_answer": "Use transforms.Compose with augmentation transforms like Rotate90, Flip, GaussianSmooth. For medical images, use spatial transforms that preserve anatomy.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["transforms", "augmentation", "composition"]}
{"id": "rag_4", "question": "Can I use MONAI with PyTorch Lightning?", "ideal_answer": "Yes, MONAI is compatible with PyTorch Lightning. Use MONAI transforms in your Dataset and Lightning Modules for end-to-end training.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["PyTorch Lightning", "integration", "training frameworks"]}
{"id": "rag_5", "question": "What embedding models does MONAI support?", "ideal_answer": "MONAI primarily focuses on medical image processing, not embeddings. For embeddings, use sentence-transformers or Hugging Face models alongside MONAI for preprocessing.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["model architectures", "feature extraction", "deep learning"]}
{"id": "rag_6", "question": "How do I load and preprocess DICOM files?", "ideal_answer": "Use MONAI's LoadImage and EnsureChannelFirst transforms. For DICOM specifically: LoadImage handles the format, then apply spatial transforms and normalization.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["DICOM loading", "file formats", "preprocessing pipeline"]}
{"id": "rag_7", "question": "What's the recommended way to do cross-validation in MONAI?", "ideal_answer": "Use sklearn's KFold or StratifiedKFold, iterate over splits, and apply MONAI transforms within each fold. Store train/val indices separately.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["cross-validation", "model evaluation", "splitting strategies"]}
{"id": "rag_8", "question": "How do I save and load MONAI models?", "ideal_answer": "Use torch.save() and torch.load() for model checkpoints. Save optimizer state, epoch, and loss for resuming training.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["model checkpoints", "saving/loading", "training state"]}
{"id": "rag_9", "question": "Can I use MONAI transforms outside of MONAI models?", "ideal_answer": "Yes, MONAI transforms are standalone PyTorch-compatible operations. Use them in any pipeline: data loading, preprocessing, augmentation.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["transforms API", "modular design", "composability"]}
{"id": "rag_10", "question": "What's the best practice for handling class imbalance in medical imaging?", "ideal_answer": "Use class weights in loss functions, data augmentation for minority classes, oversampling, or focal loss. MONAI supports weighted loss functions.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["class imbalance", "loss functions", "sampling strategies"]}
{"id": "rag_11", "question": "How do I visualize predictions during training?", "ideal_answer": "Use TensorBoard with PyTorch, log images to Weights & Biases, or save prediction volumes as NIfTI files and view in medical image viewers.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["visualization", "logging", "monitoring training"]}
{"id": "rag_12", "question": "What's the difference between spacing and shape in MONAI?", "ideal_answer": "Shape is image dimensions (e.g., 128x128x64). Spacing is voxel size in mm (e.g., 1.0x1.0x2.0). Resample changes spacing; Resize changes shape.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["image metadata", "spatial transforms", "dimensions vs spacing"]}
{"id": "rag_13", "question": "How do I implement a custom MONAI transform?", "ideal_answer": "Inherit from RandomizableTransform or Transform, implement __call__(), handle both dict and non-dict inputs. Use set_random_state() for reproducibility.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["custom transforms", "API", "transform interface"]}
{"id": "rag_14", "question": "What's the recommended backbone for medical image segmentation?", "ideal_answer": "U-Net variants (2D, 3D), ResNets with skip connections, or Vision Transformers. Choose based on model size and data availability. MONAI has U-Net implementations.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["segmentation architectures", "model selection", "network design"]}
{"id": "rag_15", "question": "How do I handle different image spacing in a batch?", "ideal_answer": "Use Spacingd transform to resample all images to a common spacing before batching. Ensures consistent voxel dimensions for network input.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["spacing normalization", "preprocessing", "batch consistency"]}
{"id": "rag_16", "question": "Can MONAI run on CPU only?", "ideal_answer": "Yes, MONAI works on CPU but is slower. For production, use GPU. For development/testing on CPU, set device='cpu' in data loaders and models.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["device support", "CPU vs GPU", "hardware requirements"]}
{"id": "rag_17", "question": "What's the best way to handle missing modalities in multi-modal medical imaging?", "ideal_answer": "Use conditional transforms that check for modality presence, pad missing channels with zeros, or use domain-specific imputation methods.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["multi-modal learning", "missing data", "conditional processing"]}
{"id": "rag_18", "question": "How do I evaluate segmentation models quantitatively?", "ideal_answer": "Use Dice coefficient, IoU, Hausdorff distance, or Surface Dice. MONAI includes metric implementations. Compare against ground truth annotations.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["evaluation metrics", "segmentation evaluation", "quantitative assessment"]}
{"id": "rag_19", "question": "What's the recommended learning rate for fine-tuning pretrained models?", "ideal_answer": "Start with lower learning rates (1e-4 to 1e-5) for pretrained weights, higher (1e-3) for randomly initialized layers. Use learning rate scheduling.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["hyperparameters", "learning rate", "fine-tuning strategy"]}
{"id": "rag_20", "question": "How do I implement ensemble predictions with multiple MONAI models?", "ideal_answer": "Load multiple trained models, run inference on test data, average predictions (soft ensemble) or take majority vote (hard ensemble).", "ground_truth_chunks": ["ensemble learning", "inference", "model aggregation"]}
{"id": "rag_21", "question": "What's the memory footprint of a 3D U-Net with 128x128x64 input?", "ideal_answer": "Depends on depth and filters, typically 4-8 GB for training with batch_size=4. Use gradient accumulation or smaller batches if memory-constrained.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["memory requirements", "model sizing", "training constraints"]}
{"id": "rag_22", "question": "Can I apply transforms to labels during augmentation?", "ideal_answer": "Yes, use dict-based transforms with keys like 'image' and 'label'. Augmentation transforms apply to both. Ensure geometric transforms match between image and label.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["label handling", "simultaneous transforms", "consistency"]}
{"id": "rag_23", "question": "How do I handle non-square 2D images (e.g., 512x256)?", "ideal_answer": "Use Resized or Pad transforms to make images square before feeding to networks. Preserve aspect ratio or pad symmetrically.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["image shape handling", "resizing", "padding strategies"]}
{"id": "rag_24", "question": "What's the best practice for distributed training with MONAI?", "ideal_answer": "Use torch.nn.DataParallel or torch.nn.parallel.DistributedDataParallel. Ensure batch sizes scale across GPUs. MONAI models are DDP-compatible.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["distributed training", "multi-GPU", "scalability"]}
{"id": "rag_25", "question": "How do I debug why my MONAI transform pipeline is slow?", "ideal_answer": "Profile with Python cProfile, check I/O (disk reads), GPU memory transfers. Use num_workers in DataLoader, pin_memory=True. Simplify transform chain if needed.", "ground_truth_chunks": ["performance optimization", "profiling", "debugging"]}
